Thera Bank Loaner¶

Data Description:¶

The dataset contains data on 5000 customers. The data include customer demographic information (age, income, etc.), the customer's relationship with the bank (mortgage, securities account, etc.), and the customer response to the last personal loan campaign (Personal Loan). Among these 5000 customers, only 480 (= 9.6%) accepted the personal loan that was offered to them in the earlier campaign.

Objective:¶

The classification goal is to predict the likelihood of a liability customer buying personal loans.

Attributes Information:¶

  • ID: Customer ID

  • Age: Customer's age in completed years

  • Experience: #years of professional experience

  • Income: Annual income of the customer ($000)

  • ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code

  • Family: Family size of the customer

  • CCAvg: Avg spending on credit cards per month ($000)

  • Education: Education Level 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate; 3: Advanced/Professional

  • Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any ($000)

  • Personal Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign?

  • Securities Account: Does the customer have a securities account with the bank?
  • CD Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank?
  • Online: Does the customer use internet banking facilities?
  • Credit card: Does the customer use a credit card issued by the bank?

Summary Insights

People observed to take a loan:¶

  • Income > 100, the higher the better the chance
  • CCAvg > 2, optimum in a range 3 - 5
  • Larger families of 3 and 4

  • People with higher education of 2 and 3

    • Group of people with Income below 100 and CCAvg below 3 are not taking a loan (must be the minimum income restriction for loan application)

In [57]:
num_df3 = num_df2.copy()

# Replace every outlier on the lower side by the lower whisker
for i, j in zip(np.where(num_df3 < Q1 - 1.5 * IQR)[0], np.where(num_df3 < Q1 - 1.5 * IQR)[1]): 
    
    whisker  = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    num_df3.iloc[i,j] = whisker[j]

#Replace every outlier on the upper side by the upper whisker    
for i, j in zip(np.where(num_df3 > Q3 + 1.5 * IQR)[0], np.where(num_df3 > Q3 + 1.5 * IQR)[1]):
    
    whisker  = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    num_df3.iloc[i,j] = whisker[j]

Model performance evaluation (accuracy, recall, precision, f1score, and roc_auc_score) with Heatmap to display confusion matrix¶

In [121]:
## function to get confusion matrix in a proper format
def draw_cm( actual, predicted ):
    cm = confusion_matrix( actual, predicted)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,  fmt='.2f', xticklabels = [0,1] , yticklabels = [0,1] )
    plt.ylabel('Observed')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()

Business Insights¶

Confusion matrix means¶

True Positive (observed=1,predicted=1):

Predicted 91 customers (from 1500 applicants) that will be taking a loan. (They were groped in a separete dataframe and can be further analyzed).

False Positive (observed=0,predicted=1):

Predicted that these customers will be taking a loan, but they did not take a loan (10 customers)

True Negative (observed=0,predicted=0):

Predicted that 1344 customers will not be taking a loan, and they did not take a loan

False Negative (observed=1,predicted=0):

Predicted that customers will not be taking a loan, but they did take a loan (55 customers)

Important Features¶

Top 5 features which were found to impact the model output, based on the highest coefficients values (from the highest to lower impact):

"Income", "CD Account", "Education", "CreditCard", "Online"

Features that doesn't help in the model predication for the target variable, based on the lowest coefficients values (close to 0, from the lowest to higher impact):

"Mortgage", "Age" and "Experience".

Important Metric¶

Here the bank wants to suggest a loan to customers and benefit from the loan sale, i.e. less number of False Negative, if FN is high, bank would loss money by not suggesting them to apply for a loan. Hence Recall score (Sensitivity) is the important metric, if FN is high, bank would loss money wihtout potential loan customers.

In case of False positive bank will lose some money on advertisement which will not reach the target. The F1 score (the weighted average of the Precision and the recall scores) can be second important metric in this case.

The model can be deployed for practical use, as Thera Bank can target loan customers and predict who will be interested in taking a loan. They can use the model for upcoming customers.
